==English==

===Etymology===
Compound of {{compound|en|metric|system}}, from {{der|en|fr|métrique}}. See also {{m|en|meter}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈmɛtɹɪk ˌsɪstəm/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|?}}

# The system of measurements developed in France in the 1790s and now used worldwide.
# The modern version of that system, {{w|Systeme Internationale d'Unites}} ([[International System of Units]]), or [[SI]] system of measurements that is based on the [[base unit]]s of the [[meter]]/[[metre]], the [[kilogram]], the [[second]], the [[ampere]], the [[kelvin]], the [[mole]], and the [[candela]].
#: see [[Appendix:SI_units|Appendix on SI Units]]
# Any variant of that system, that was not codified as SI, such as [[cgs]].

